{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e104231b-257b-4a4c-8cc6-402bee2cc79f","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find recent reports:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\" to browse them with a GUI.\n\nThese `.ips` files contain the full native backtrace, register state, and loaded images — enough to investigate most NativeAOT crashes. If you share the `.ips` file, I can help symbolicate the .NET runtime frames.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ad24a4c-5850-4f91-ac25-4752dc89b282","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting — I can answer directly.","outputTokens":298,"requestId":"6401:311A36:E3CFDBC:FD55FF6:69EC19C7"},"id":"c7535c06-19c7-4732-bcab-bee51f55e0b3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:33:02.929Z","parentId":"808589de-2ff5-4c9c-8f11-639620d6758b"}
